"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\">Color coded resistors are shown in the procedures.</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\"> </span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\">1.4</span><span style=\" font-family:\'Times New Roman\'; font-size:7pt; color:#00007f;\">         </span><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\">Theory</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt; color:#00007f;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\">1.4.1</span><span style=\" font-family:\'Times New Roman\'; font-size:7pt; color:#00007f;\">            </span><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\">Ammeter</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt; color:#00007f;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\">An ammeter is an instrument used for measuring current. It is included in series with a branch of a circuit so that it passess all the current through the branch. An ammeter should be connected or bridged series any circuit element for this might have sufficient voltage to cause a much greater current in the instrument than the rated value. The ammeter resistance is usually very small so that there is no significant voltage drop across it.</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\"-qt-paragraph-type:empty; margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; font-size:8pt;\"><br /></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\">         </span><span style=\" font-size:18pt; color:#00007f;\"> </span><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\"> 1.4.2  Voltmeter</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\">A voltmeter is an instrument used to measure voltage. It is connected directly across the points whose potential difference is to be measured. A voltmeter has high resistance so as not to draw a significant portion of the load current the higher the voltage range the higher is its resistance.</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\"> </span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600;\">         </span><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\"> 1.4.3  Ohmmeter</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt; color:#00007f;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\">An ohmmeter is an instrument used to measure resistance. Resistance measurement with an ohmmeter is made with the resistor removed from the circuit.</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\"> </span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\">The ammeter, the voltmeter and the ohmmeter all use a basic d’arsonoval movement. The difference between these instruments is the circuit in which the movement is used. It is, therefore, obvious that an instrument can be designed to perform the three measurement functions. This instrument which contains a function switch to connect the appropriate circuits so the d’arsonoval movement, is often called multimeter or volt-ohm-millimmeter(VOM).</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\"> </span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\">2</span><span style=\" font-size:18pt; color:#00007f;\">  </span><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\"> Procedures</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt; color:#00007f;\"> </span></p>\n"
