"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\">Frequency measurement </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\">There methods for measuring frequency of a signal with an oscilloscope will be discussed.</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\">i)</span><span style=\" font-family:\'Times New Roman\'; font-size:7pt; color:#00007f;\">                  </span><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\">Reciprocal time interval:</span><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\"> measuring the time interval between corresponding points on consecutive cycles of a signal waveform and taking its reciprocal gives the frequency of the signal.</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\">ii)</span><span style=\" font-family:\'Times New Roman\'; font-size:7pt; color:#00007f;\">               </span><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\">Lissajous figure:</span><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600;\"> </span><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\">this is a comparison method primarly used to determine the frequency ratio between two sinusoids. If the frequency of one sine wave is known then the other can be determined. </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\">a common practice is to connect the signal of known(standard) frequency to the horizontal input and the unknown frequency to the vertical input. One or more loops will appear in the display. The ratio of loops tangent to the horizontal line to the number of loops tangent to the vertical line determines the ratio of the frequencies of the vertical and the horizontal input signals. In general </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><img src=\"file:///C:/Users/Habtamu/AppData/Local/Packages/oice_16_974fa576_32c1d314_2c2d/AC/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_image037.png\" width=\"502\" height=\"62\" /><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\">this technique is very useful calibrating sine wave oscillators.</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\"> </span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\"> </span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p align=\"center\" style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><img src=\"file:///C:/Users/Habtamu/AppData/Local/Packages/oice_16_974fa576_32c1d314_2c2d/AC/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_image038.png\" width=\"498\" height=\"282\" /><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\">iii)</span><span style=\" font-family:\'Times New Roman\'; font-size:7pt; color:#00007f;\">            </span><span style=\" font-size:18pt; font-weight:600; color:#00007f;\">Intensity modulation </span></p>\n"
"<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\"><span style=\" font-size:18pt;\">Lissajous pattern for large ratios of frequency are difficult to interpret apart from the complexity of the pattern as any slight in frequency will cause the pattern to roll. In such cases a method used is to supply the signal voltage under measurement to the X and Y inputs, with some phase shift introduce by a phase shifting circuit(to give an elliptic display) and applying a higher frequency signal to the Z modulator input (control grid of the CRT). This higher frequency signal varies the intensity of the elliptic display, there being one bright and one dark section for each of this frequency. This method, while giving a display which is easy to implement, is limited in application to exact multiples of input frequencies.</span><span style=\" font-size:8pt;\"> </span></p>\n"
